    "title": "Security, Pairing and Authentication",
    "synopsis": "security_auth",
    "description": "Guide on physical pairing via 6-digit PIN, HttpOnly cookies, and brute-force lockout protection.",
    "details": "NAME\n  security_auth - Device pairing, session authentication, and access control models.\n\nDESCRIPTION\n  NucleoOS establishes a strict pairing boundary. Physical proximity verification is mandatory to access hardware peripherals or personal data stores.\n\n  1. PAIRING PROTOCOL (PHYSICAL PROXIMITY):\n     - The microcontroller displays an autogenerated 6-digit PIN on its local LCD screen.\n     - The browser client sends this PIN to the `/api/pair` HTTP POST endpoint.\n     - If valid, the server replies with a `Set-Cookie` header containing a 24-byte random hex token marked as `HttpOnly` and `SameSite=Lax`.\n\n  2. STABLE SESSIONS:\n     - Active session tokens are stored in the non-volatile LittleFS configuration partition under `/cfg/config/auth.json` (max 8 concurrent slots).\n     - This allows trusted clients to bypass PIN prompts across hardware power cycles.\n     - Oldest sessions are evicted in a ring-write pattern when a 9th device pairs.\n\n  3. BRUTE-FORCE PROTECTION:\n     - After 5 consecutive PIN validation failures, `/api/pair` blocks requests returning HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests) for a 30-second cooldown window.\n\n  4. PUBLIC VS PROTECTED GATEWAY STATUS:\n     - Protected: `/api/fs/*`, `/api/rec/*`, `/api/ota`, `/ws`.\n     - Public: `/`, static assets, `/api/status`, `/api/apps`, `/api/associations`, `/api/pair`."
  }
